We seek a particular solution since the homogeneous solution will decay
to 0 as $t \rightarrow \infty$. As $\sin(2t) = \text{Im}(e^{2it})$, we
will look for a particular solution of form $x(t) = \text{Im}(\phi(t))$
where $\phi = A e^{2it}$ satisfies the ODE in complex form:

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle \phi'' + 2 \phi' + 5 \phi = e^{2it}
\end{align*}

so that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
-4 A e^{2it} + 4 i A e^{2it} + 5 A e^{2it} = e^{2it}
\end{align*}

which upon cancelling the $e^{2it}$ terms and simplification becomes

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
A (1 + 4 i) = 1
\end{align*}

Solving for \emph{A} we obtain

\begin{align*}
A = \frac{1}{1 + 4i} = \frac{1 - 4i}{(1 + 4i)(1 - 4i)} = \frac{1 - 4i}{17}.
\end{align*}

Now that we have A, we can find x by using A and Euler's identity:

\begin{align*}
x(t) &= \text{Im}\left(\frac{1-4i}{17} e^{2it}\right) \\
&= \frac1{17}\text{Im}((1-4i) (\cos(2t) + i \sin(2t)) \\
&= \frac1{17}\text{Im}(\cos(2t) + 4 \sin(2t) + i (\sin(2t) - 4 \cos(2t))) \\
&= \frac{1}{17} \sin(2t) - \frac{4}{17} \cos(2t)
\end{align*}

The steady solution is
$x(t) = \frac{1}{17} \sin(2t) - \frac{4}{17} \cos(2t)$.
